        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "Perhaps as a simple starting point we could use the following format:\r\n\r\n```\r\nnote    src/main.rs:2:9-13  remove this `mut`\r\nwarning src/main.rs:2:9-20  variable does not need to\r\nnote    src/main.rs:2:13-20 if this is intentional\r\nwarning src/main.rs:2:13-20 unused variable: `number`\r\n```\r\n\r\nThat is:\r\n\r\n```\r\nkind path:line:start-col:stop-col message\r\n```\r\n\r\nWhere each column is padded on the right so everything aligns nicely.\r\n\r\nThis contains the same information as the current default, but should be a tad easier on the eyes. Personally I prefer just signs for item types (e.g. `W` instead of `warning`), but I think full names are better as a starting point. There are two points of discussion though:\r\n\r\n1. Do we implement this in Lua, or fiddle around with it in C? I'm thinking Lua might be best in case we need to backport quickfix code from Vim\r\n2. We need to change the `qf` syntax rules for this new format. The [default rules](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/09e96fe6096f07365eb65b51bb7f2fd0f1b043b0/runtime/syntax/qf.vim) are super specific about where they expect certain values. I guess an `after/qf.vim` file would be suitable for this?",
